DESCRIPTION
Dogfooding a closed bead currently takes N separate 'etude capture <stage>' calls (one per phase: plan/implement/verify/review), each repeating the same --run/--harness/--git-sha/--workflow/--ref flags, plus a manual ref push. scripts/dogfood-capture.sh now wraps this, but the durable product fix is a first-class batch mode: e.g. 'etude capture --manifest run.yaml' (or 'etude capture-run') that takes one spec describing all stages (stage, skill, model, inputs, output) and writes them as a single run in one invocation, sharing the common run-level metadata. Reduces dogfood toil and makes import-from-spec coherent with the capture-protocol doc. Came out of the Phase 3 evaluator retro (eval-interface/rubric-eval/pairwise-eval); interim tool is scripts/dogfood-capture.sh.

DESIGN
## Plan

**Approach:** Add a NEW top-level command `etude capture-run <spec.yaml>` (a sibling
of `capture`/`capture-gate`, NOT a `--manifest` mode of `capture`). Rationale: batch
capture has a fundamentally different shape than single-stage capture (a spec file, no
stage arg, N stages, run-level defaults). Overloading `capture` with a mutually-exclusive
`--manifest` mode that ignores its stage arg + most of its ~15 flags would be a worse
surface than a clean separate command. The new command parses ONE YAML spec into a full
multi-stage `runmanifest.Manifest` + a `files` map (artifacts read via
`artifactstore.AddContent`, exactly like `addFileArtifact` in capture.go), then writes the
whole thing in ONE `runmanifest.WriteManifestTree(ctx, store, "refs/etude/runs/", manifest,
files, refstore.WriteOptions{})` call (create-only; ExpectedOld="") â€” mirroring how
`runmanifest.Writer.Write` delegates. No reinvention: reuse the existing yaml.v3 dep
(already in go.mod, used by internal/workflow), `artifactstore`, `WriteManifestTree`,
`Manifest.Validate`, and capture.go's helpers (`inferMediaType`, `validateGitSHA`,
`currentHEAD`, `parseRefs`, `validateCLIIdentifier`).

Decisions resolved:
1. Command surface: NEW `etude capture-run <spec>` (justified above). One positional arg =
   the spec path. A single `--message` flag for the commit message; everything else lives
   in the spec.
2. Spec schema (YAML, KnownFields(true) like workflow.ParseYAML). Run-level: `run_id`
   (optional â€” auto-allocate via replay.AllocateRunID if omitted; require valid id if given),
   `workflow` (default \"manual\"), `workflow_version` (default \"manual-v1\"), `git_sha`
   (default = currentHEAD), `harness`, `harness_version`, `model`, `produced_by`
   (default \"original\"), `skill_repo`/`skill_version` defaults (default \"manual\"/\"manual\"),
   top-level `refs` (map[string]string). Plus `stages:` list â€” each stage: `stage` (name),
   `produced_by` (override), `git_sha` (override), `skill` ({id, repo, version} â€” id required,
   repo/version fall back to run-level defaults), `model` (override), `harness`/
   `harness_version` (override), `inputs:` list of {role, path}, `output:` {role, path}.
   Every field grounds in runmanifest.Manifest/Stage/Producer/Skill so it round-trips.
   Artifact PATHS resolve RELATIVE TO THE SPEC FILE's directory (so a self-contained spec
   dir is portable); document this clearly. Each stage builds one runmanifest.Stage with
   Producer{Harness,Model,Skill} + Skill mirror (matching capture.go lines 190-211).
3. Single-run write: build whole Manifest (Created=now, all Stages with per-stage now-ish
   timestamps) + merged files map, ONE WriteManifestTree call, create-only (ExpectedOld=\"\").
   Run id: if spec omits run_id, allocate via replay.AllocateRunID(ctx, store, base) where
   base is derived from spec (require an explicit `run_id` OR a `run_id_base` â€” decision:
   require explicit run_id for v1 to keep it deterministic for dogfood; auto-allocate is a
   noted future option). Reject if ref already exists (create-only error surfaced clearly).
4. Push: write LOCALLY ONLY, consistent with `capture`/`capture-gate`. Push stays the
   operator's job (`git push` / `etude sync`); do NOT bundle push into the product command.
   (dogfood-capture.sh's push moves into the wrapper / follow-up, not here.)
5. Validation + errors: spec missing/unreadable -> clear error; malformed YAML / unknown
   fields -> rejected via KnownFields(true); missing required run-level metadata (run_id,
   per-stage skill.id, at least one stage, exactly one output per stage) -> explicit errors;
   artifact path that doesn't exist -> \"read <path>: ...\"; Manifest.Validate failures
   surface through WriteManifestTree unchanged.

